reviews.review_text: Joe does it again!!! Once again, Joe's copy is currently the best available source for this source. I don't like this show as well as the other two nights from the run but it does have the first breakout Box Of Rain since '73. Don't get me wrong, this show does have other redeeming qualities and is worth the dl.
the perfect recording spot just too much of a big boom, the echo is sweet, daddy like

A Show of great Histeric Import. Was at this show.  As usual with Hampton, it rained.  A LOT.  EVERYONE was cooped up in their cars all day watching the raindrops run down the windshield.  Have had a copy since the day of the show, but never one as good as this.  

Some items of note are that the ALTHEA is the cause for the "practice makes perfect quip".  I don't know WHAT happened there.  I have never heard a louder crowd response to anything at any show ever than to Box of Rain breakout.  Estimated is one of the all-time greatest ham jobs.  The sound on the drums and space is really amazing and this could actually be the highlight of the show.  Brent stays out with the drums for some tasty jamming.  Pretty unusual.

I'm giving a 4 for its histeric value & b/c I am just another picky Deadhead, which if you knew them boys only makes sense.

There are other great moments in this show Yes, Box of Rain was like a drink of cool water. But you would be amiss if you stopped there. I would put the Iko against any other version. There is a fantastic Desi Arnaz jam at the end. You can tell the band is having fun. The Estimated killed brain cells. Yes it was an echo fest, but a real psychedelic one. The jam after the echo fest into eyes is beautiful jazz music. The Eyes is stellar into an extended Brent Drumz Space jam into a wonderfully melancholy wharf rat.  In short don't stop listening after the Box and crank up the Iko>Estimated>Eyes. Hidden magic. Enjoy.
Nice Find Highlights: Box Of Rain, Estimated Prophet

WTC Remembrance This show and the previous night were the last two Dead shows I went to. Road trip from Poughkeepsie NY, with my good friend and bandmate Vinny Kane, who later became a NYC firefighter and perished in the South Tower of the World Trade Center on September 11, 2001. What a trip we had, laughing all the way down the NYS Thruway, to the Jersey Turnpike, over the Delaware Memorial Bridge, the Chesapeake Bay Bridge-Tunnel into Hampton Roads. The afternoon before this show we went to the Virginia Air and Space Visitors center. Such great memories spent with a great friend. God bless you, Vinny Kane. Pray for us.
